{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_012iMz7bLePkSgHbXcpfZPdi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good understanding of the changes. Let me read the full title-extractor.ts to understand the complete context, and then launch the review agents. Actually, I already have the full file content from the first read. Let me now launch the review agents in parallel.\n\nGiven this is a text-processing heuristics module for mobile (not a web API, no auth, no DB), the relevant review aspects are:\n- Code Quality (the main concern for heuristic code)\n- Performance (mobile device, 10s budget)\n- Testing Quality (test coverage of new patterns)\n- Architecture (moderate concern - complexity growth)\n\nSecurity and Documentation are less relevant here. Let me launch focused agents.\n\n\nActually, I've already read through all the code and understand the changes thoroughly, so I'll do the review myself rather than spinning up multiple agents. This is more efficient for a single-file heuristic change. Let me work through the changes against the improvement plan to spot any issues.\n\nThe implementation covers all 4 patterns from the plan: the blind OCR repair gets extracted and applied early to candidates in the first few positions, the contextual title matching uses the surrounding text to refine results, the fallback chain handles edge cases progressively, and the scoring system weights different signals appropriately.\n\nPattern 4 involves several interconnected changes—the threshold for detecting cooking instructions gets stricter, the corroboration check now considers where in the document we are, burst detection propagates through the scoring pipeline, and the logic for identifying pages without titles expands to catch more cases where the content reads like body prose rather than a title.\n\nNow I'm checking the `isBodyProse` function that identifies Polish text—it uses a regex matching lowercase letters and Polish diacritics, which works fine for this Polish/English recipe context, though it wouldn't catch accented characters from other Romance languages if they ever appeared in recipe names.\n\nThe `startsWithNumber` function handles Unicode fractions nicely, which is practical since recipes frequently use characters like ½ and ⅓ in ingredient measurements.\n\nI'm noticing a potential issue with the direct-successor bonus: it adds +0.10 to the top 3 candidates on top of the existing positional boost, so the first candidate could end up with +0.25 total (+0.15 capped positional boost plus +0.10 direct-successor bonus), which might be stacking bonuses in an unintended way.\n\nThe improvement plan suggests these bonuses should share the same +0.15 cap, but the implementation applies the cap first, then adds the direct-successor bonus separately. This looks like a deviation from the plan, though the tests are passing, so maybe this over-boost is actually helping with edge cases. I should flag this as something to investigate further.\n\nNow I'm looking at some duplication issues. There's overlap between `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` and `SECTION_LABELS` — entries like \"vegetables\" and \"seafood\" appear in both — which is intentional since one is a subset of the other, but the values aren't derived programmatically, so they could drift if one gets updated. That's a minor maintainability concern I can live with for now.\n\nThe `findBurstEnd` overflow detection also got some improvements with better blank line tracking and ALL_CAPS heading detection, and the guard logic looks solid.\n\nBut I'm noticing the fallback changed from `k + 1` to `m` when no termination is found, which means it skips all the way to the end of the lines array — that could be too aggressive. Though looking at the outer loop constraints, this only runs on the first 30 lines and only when specific overflow markers match, so it's actually pretty limited in scope.\n\nNow I'm checking the regex chains in `applyBlindOcrRepair` — there are 10+ replacements, but since it only runs on candidates at position 5 or less with OCR artifacts, that's at most around 5 calls, so performance isn't really a concern here.\n\nFor `passesCorroboration` with the `startLine` parameter, I'm wondering if there's a correctness issue. The function only looks at lines after `burstEnd`, meaning a title candidate's words must appear in the post-spillover portion. But if the candidate itself is in the spillover region, that seems contradictory. Let me trace through `buildCandidates` to see if spillover candidates even exist...\n\nActually, `buildCandidates` uses `burstEnd` to skip the spillover region entirely, so candidates only come from after that point. That resolves it.\n\nFor the `isTitleAbsentPage` and `isBodyProse` interaction, adding the prose check means a page starting with 3+ prose lines counts as title-absent. The concern is whether a real title in sentence case could be misclassified, but `isBodyProse` specifically checks for a lowercase starting character, which titles wouldn't have. So that should be safe.\n\nNow I'm noticing a real problem: the direct-successor bonus isn't capped. If the first candidate gets both the first-after-preamble bonus of +0.12 and the direct-successor bonus of +0.10, that's +0.25 total, which exceeds the intended +0.15 maximum. The cap logic only applies to the first-after-preamble bonus itself, not to the combined effect when both bonuses apply.\n\nThe direct-successor bonus applies to the top 3 candidates, so candidates 2 and 3 get it uncapped anyway, but the first candidate is the one where this stacking becomes problematic. I should flag this as a medium-priority issue and check whether the tests still pass if I adjust the cap to include both bonuses or reorder the logic.\n\nLet me run the tests to see the current state.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11642,"cache_read_input_tokens":39882,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11642},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4cf8a7d1-939d-4c00-8b9d-2a05046808fb","uuid":"6c9ef1c6-20c4-4997-ac1a-4d82d74eddc8"}
